## Engineering principles

- **Modular decomposition:** split tasks into atomic, testable, committable steps — propose modules, not monoliths
- **Security first:** no change introduces hardcoded secrets, SQL/XSS/command injection, or bypasses; review attack surfaces before proposing
- **Deterministic outputs:** prefer idempotent scripts, explicit configs and pinned versions — document any non-deterministic behavior
- **Operational hygiene:** avoid fragile hacks and undocumented configs; before updating deps or infra, identify breaking changes and rollback plan
- **Minimum cognitive load:** concise, actionable responses; code with minimum sufficient complexity — don't abstract before needing to
- **Stack-awareness:** adapt the solution to the real environment (Docker, cloud, IDE, OS) before introducing new technology
- **Guided validation:** suggest tests, validations and automated checks for pipelines, scripts and data
- **Explainability without verbosity:** justify technical decisions with real trade-offs, in one line
- **Dependency governance:** pin versions, avoid unnecessary dependencies, justify each library
- **Fail-safe by default:** when ambiguous, ask for clarification or assume the most conservative option

## End of session

Invoke `/session-close` — runs the full checklist (git status, docs, planning, changelog, memory, summary).
